Baby’s first @ted talk: “3-2-1 Action!” ♥️

Flew from LA to Istanbul for three days to go up on that holy stage and speak my mind for 18 minutes. 

And this time, I didn’t talk about my directing, my music videos, or my background. I wanted to peel back all those layers and try to touch the core– what is it about my approach to life and actions that made me do the things I did and get to where I am?

I hope it ignites a flame in you and inspires you to act despite everyone and everything 🔥

It was honestly the hardest thing I’ve ever done but I couldn’t be happier that I did it. Thank you @tedxizmit for inviting me and your amazing hospitality. Thank you everyone for coming in person, it was the best feeling to meet and hug you all after.

And thank you to the incredible @melistatari for styling me the night before, letting me rehearse until you passed out, and not leaving my side the whole time. Thank you @banuyorulmaz @yildirayorulmaz for being my glam fam who perfectly camouflaged my lack of sleep for three days– looking the part made me feel like I could do it 🙏🏼

“3-2-1 Action!” will be yours soon! 

📸 @gorucoglu

Los Angeles’tan üç günlüğüne İstanbul’a, 18 dakikalığına o sahnede içimi dökmeye geldim. 

Bu sefer yönetmenliğimi, kliplerimi veya geçmişimi konuşmak yerine, bütün o katmanların altında, çekirdekte yatan şeyi ortaya çıkarmak istedim– ne türlü bir hayata bakışın ve aksiyonlarımın yaptığım şeyleri yapmama ve geldiğim yere gelmeme sebep olduklarını sorguladım.

Umarım içinizdeki bir koru tutuşturur, herkese ve her şeye rağmen harekete geçmeniz için size ilham olur 🔥

İlk Ted Talk’um “3-2-1 Aksiyon!” çok yakında sizlerle♥️

Nazlı Offringa & Ecem Lawton

Following the earthquake disaster in Turkey, an urgent need for baby food arose in the affected areas. Babies are starving, necessary formulas aren't reaching the necessary regions, and liquid formulas are not available in Turkey.

Dr. Nazlı Offringa met with big baby food companies in the USA and got approval for donations in huge quantities, but these FDA-approved formulas are not approved in Turkey.

This critical need, which wants to be met by large companies in America, must be urgently approved by the Turkish Ministry of Health.

Please support the delivery of food to mothers and babies by signing our campaign!

#DerinMevzular yayında!

Inspired by Dostoevsky's "The Double," Derin Mevzular (Deep Issues) tells the tale of a white collar office drone who leads the most monotonous of lives. He is invisible, viewed with pity and contempt in the banal spaces he occupies. One night, smoking, drinking, watching TV, he sees HIMSELF as a wanted criminal in a breaking news broadcast. Initially surprised, he is soon hypnotized by his alter ego’s illicit activities. As he “fantasizes” about his Doppelgänger, a lothario who represents everything he is not—a sexy criminal mastermind as compared to the boring dude who mans the printer at the office—the line between fantasy and reality blurs. Does he really have a Doppelgänger living a sex- and violence-filled Hollywood life? Or is this merely a dream of a ridiculous man? The ending suggests the answer is “both,” a final mystery for viewers to puzzle over as they search for Easter eggs in the video — of which there are more than a few 🥚

Dostoyevski'nin "Çift" (The Double) romanından esinlenen Derin Mevzular, monoton bir hayat süren, beyaz yaka bir ofis çalışanının hikayesini anlatır. Adeta görünmezdir, işgal ettiği sıradan alanlarda ona acıma ile bakılır ve hor görülür. Yine bir gece sigara, içki ve televizyon ışığı tüketirken bir son dakika haber programında KENDİNİ aranan bir suçlu olarak görür. Baştaki şaşkınlığı kısa bir süre içinde alter egosunun bu yasadışı faaliyetlerine karşı hipnotize olmasına dönüşür. Doppelgänger'ı, onun gerçek hayatta olmadığı her şeyi temsil eder –ofiste printerla kavga eden bir adama karşın, çapkın, seksi bir suç dehası– ve gerçekle hayal arasındaki çizgi bulanıklaşır. Gerçekten seks ve şiddet dolu bir hayat yaşayan Doppelgänger'ı var mıdır? Yoksa bu deneyimlediği sadece gülünç bir adamın rüyası mıdır? Klibin sonu, bu soruların cevabının “ikisi de” olduğunu ima eder ve bu gizemin çözümünü klibin içindeki ipuçlarıyla izleyiciye bırakır. 🫣

1. Puree 1 cup blackberries & 1.5 cup yoghurt 
2. In a separate bowl, mix 1 cup yoghurt, squeeze of honey, juice of 1 lemon + zest and a few drops of vanilla
3. In popsicle molds, layer 1 tb of blackberry mix & 1 layer of yoghurt, keep going until full. You can also use icecube trays if you don't have the molds.

Our film Guvanch People just won the Best Fashion Film award at Style, Experimental, Fashion Film Festival!

New York City is freedom. It is and has always been a place for people to experiment with their identities and to be who they truly are. This fashion film featuring Guvanch NYC designs represents the beauty of that freedom all across the topography of the city by way of the opulent directorial style of Ecem Lawton. It portrays this in a freewheeling mode that captures the delirious joy of being different in NYC. 

The first part shows the reality of daily life with its rhythms and routines, whereas the second shows the oozing eroticism of the city's queer nightlife. Indeed, the film as a whole revels in the beauty of queer liberation that is such a big and beautiful part of the fabric of NYC.

Big love to our amazing team and the audience members who voted!

memoirs of a hot shoot on a cold night 🔮🔮🔮

They say never meet your heroes... But I'm so grateful to have met mine, and to have shared a little time with Nuri Bilge Ceylan–one of the ten best directors in the world today without a doubt. 

Studying his movies made me passionate about slow cinema, how his highly composed, drawn-out shots liberated his audience to consume the work as if they were analyzing a painting, whereas fast cuts limited what they could see, understand, and reflect on. Nuri Bilge's cinema wasn't manipulative, it allowed the audience to approach movies like paintings, using art as a tool to create meaning rather than one that imposes meanings. 

Studying him religiously in my film classes at @columbia and writing my senior thesis on him made me decide to then get a masters in Contemporary Art just because he taught me how to sit with a picture over long periods of time and derive new meanings from such lengthy engagements. 

When it came to Nuri Bilge, I always questioned what made him so great. Is it an aura one detects, a way of speaking, a lens through which one sees the world? Having had the honor of interpreting for him (not that he needed it most of the time) on his press tour for his new movie "About Dry Grasses," the Turkish entry for the Best International Feature Film at @theacademy, I know that greatness IS an aura that surrounds a person and influences all that they do. I learned so much from just his way of being, speaking, and seeing. Thank you Nuri Hoca for all the laughs, your humility, and your understated greatness.

Thank you @barbarostapan @janus_films for thinking of me.♥️
